        "text": "Short answer: It’s truly global now, with the heaviest concentration of activity in North America, Europe, and Asia–Pacific, and especially strong momentum in cloud/devops, financial services, telecom/edge, automotive, energy/utilities, public sector, healthcare, AI/ML, and data infrastructure. Below are the regions and industries showing the most adoption and/or innovation, with primary sources you can dig into.\n\nHow “open source” is defined\n- Open source definition and criteria: Open Source Initiative (OSI) Open Source Definition https://opensource.org/osd\n\nRegions seeing strong adoption/innovation\n- Global picture and contribution hotspots\n  - GitHub State of the Octoverse (country/region developer activity, fastest-growing communities, and project trends): https://octoverse.github.com/\n  - Linux Foundation Research (global and regional open source adoption/impact studies): https://www.linuxfoundation.org/research\n  - Red Hat State of Enterprise Open Source 2024 (enterprise adoption across regions): https://www.redhat.com/en/resources/state-of-enterprise-open-source-2024\n  - Synopsys OSSRA 2024 (open source presence across codebases in many industries): https://www.synopsys.com/software-integrity/resources/analyst-reports/ossra.html\n\n- North America\n  - Large, mature OSS user and contributor base; enterprise adoption and cloud-native leadership highlighted across Octoverse and CNCF surveys:\n    - GitHub Octoverse: https://octoverse.github.com/\n    - CNCF Reports/Surveys (cloud-native adoption by region and industry): https://www.cncf.io/reports/\n\n- Europe\n  - Strong government policy backing and enterprise/community ecosystems; EU institutions formalizing open source strategy:\n    - European Commission Open Source Strategy: https://commission.europa.eu/resources-partners/european-commission-open-source-strategy-2020-2023_en\n    - Linux Foundation Research (European spotlights appear within global studies): https://www.linuxfoundation.org/research\n\n- Asia–Pacific\n  - Rapid growth in developer communities and cloud-native adoption:\n    - GitHub Octoverse: https://octoverse.github.com/\n    - CNCF Reports (APAC trends in Kubernetes/cloud-native): https://www.cncf.io/reports/\n    - Example of homegrown AI/ML OSS from the region: PaddlePaddle (Baidu) https://www.paddlepaddle.org.cn/\n\n- Africa and Latin America\n  - Fast-growing developer communities and strong public-health and civic-tech adoption:\n    - GitHub Octoverse (growth indicators): https://octoverse.github.com/\n    - DHIS2 (open-source health information system used by many ministries of health): https://dhis2.org/\n    - OpenMRS (open-source EMR platform used in many countries): https://openmrs.org/\n    - openEHR (open health records specification/community): https://www.openehr.org/\n\nIndustries leading in adoption/innovation\n- Cloud, containers, and devops (cross-industry)\n  - Broad, mainstream use of cloud-native tech and Kubernetes across regions and sectors:\n    - CNCF Cloud Native Survey/Reports: https://www.cncf.io/reports/\n    - Kubernetes: https://kubernetes.io/\n\n- Financial services\n  - Banks, fintechs, and market infrastructures are formalizing participation (OSPOs, contribution policies) and collaborating on shared stacks:\n    - FINOS (Linux Foundation; annual “State of Open Source in Financial Services”): https://www.finos.org/research\n    - Linux Foundation Research (sector-specific reports often include finance): https://www.linuxfoundation.org/research\n\n- Telecommunications and networking (including edge/5G/RAN)\n  - Open networking stacks and disaggregated, programmable networks are largely driven by OSS:\n    - O-RAN ALLIANCE (open RAN interfaces/ecosystem): https://www.o-ran.org/\n    - ONAP (LF Networking; network automation platform): https://www.onap.org/\n    - Linux Foundation Networking (project umbrella): https://lfnetworking.org/\n\n- Automotive and mobility\n  - Shared software platforms for in-vehicle systems and tooling:\n    - Automotive Grade Linux (AGL): https://www.automotivelinux.org/\n\n- Energy and utilities\n  - Grid modernization, interoperability, and DER integration via collaborative OSS stacks:\n    - LF Energy (projects and case studies across utilities): https://www.lfenergy.org/\n\n- Public sector and defense\n  - Policies encouraging reuse, transparency, and contribution; formal OSPOs in governments:\n    - European Commission Open Source Strategy: https://commission.europa.eu/resources-partners/european-commission-open-source-strategy-2020-2023_en\n    - U.S. DoD memo on improving open source software use (policy direction): https://dodcio.defense.gov/News/News-Display/Article/3502044/department-of-defense-releases-memorandum-to-improve-open-source-software-use/\n\n- Healthcare and global health\n  - Widespread use in national health information systems and clinical platforms, especially in LMICs:\n    - DHIS2: https://dhis2.org/\n    - OpenMRS: https://openmrs.org/\n    - openEHR: https://www.openehr.org/\n\n- AI/ML and data science\n  - Explosive growth in open-source model tooling, frameworks, and model-sharing hubs:\n    - GitHub Octoverse (AI repo growth trends): https://octoverse.github.com/\n    - PyTorch: https://pytorch.org/\n    - TensorFlow: https://www.tensorflow.org/\n    - Hugging Face: https://huggingface.co/\n\n- Data infrastructure and analytics (cross-industry staples)\n  - Core platforms remain predominantly open source and are widely deployed:\n    - Apache Kafka: https://kafka.apache.org/\n    - Apache Spark: https://spark.apache.org/\n    - PostgreSQL: https://www.postgresql.org/\n    - Stack Overflow Developer Survey 2024 (technology usage/affinity trends): https://survey.stackoverflow.co/2024/\n\nHow to interpret “most”\n- If you mean “most enterprises using OSS,” look at enterprise surveys:\n  - Red Hat State of Enterprise Open Source 2024: https://www.redhat.com/en/resources/state-of-enterprise-open-source-2024\n  - Synopsys OSSRA 2024 (open source in commercial codebases): https://www.synopsys.com/software-integrity/resources/analyst-reports/ossra.html\n- If you mean “largest contributor bases or project velocity,” use developer/activity data:\n  - GitHub Octoverse: https://octoverse.github.com/\n  - CNCF ecosystem growth and end-user reports: https://www.cncf.io/reports/\n- If you mean “policy-led adoption,” watch public-sector strategies:\n  - European Commission Open Source Strategy: https://commission.europa.eu/resources-partners/european-commission-open-source-strategy-2020-2023_en\n  - U.S. DoD OSS memo: https://dodcio.defense.gov/News/News-Display/Article/3502044/department-of-defense-releases-memorandum-to-improve-open-source-software-use/\n\nIf you share which “most” (usage, contributions, new projects, policy, etc.) you care about, I can filter these sources to a focused, data-backed short list.",
